D6-brane Charges 
Now we can compute the charges of the system. The metric on the transverse space can be written as

ds^2_TN =r+m r-m dr^2+(r^2-m^2)d^2_(2) +(4m)^2r-m r+m (d+ 2 d)^2,
so the vector potential and its field strenght are

A&=&2md,

F&=&dA=-2mdd.
From here one can compute the NUT charge as 

N=1 8 F=m.
It is interesting to mention that the parameter  is set, from boundary conditions to be

4m=l_se^_0 
where  is the boundary value of the dilaton of the type IIA string theory.

The magnetic charge of the monopole can be computed from the integral of the totally antisymmetric part of the spin connection minus the background , where  is the Killing vector representing the isometry, which is, up to a normalization factor

r-m r+m  2 ddd.
This form is proportional to the volume form of the  which means that it can be interpreted as a winding number. The corresponding charge is

K=1 16^2 The metric () is self-dual, i.e. , which, in turn, implies that the mass of the solution is equal to its NUT charge, and has a positive orientation defined by an orthonormal frame which can be chosen in such a way that

e^& = & (r-m r+m )^1/2 (4md+2md),

e^r       & = & (r+m r-m )^1/2 dr,
where we have just written the two components that will be interesting for us. 

At this moment we have computed three of the charges of the system, and this would be all if we do not consider the vector potentials associated with the 3-form of M-theory.

In order to define now the electric charge we will use the following strategy. Since we are considering an eleven dimensional supergravity solution, we will use the M-theory 3-form . The pieces of  that will be relevant for our discussion are the 2-form  and the 1-form  defined in (). Notice that these forms are associated, respectively, with the gauge field  and the 2-form  on the D6-brane world-volume.

Using (), we observe that the 2-form  is a pure gauge. It is this pure gauge 2-form the one that is playing for the eleven dimensional KK-monopole case the same role that a pure gauge 2-form  in the case of the ten dimensional KK-monopole. In this sense we will define the electric charge as associated with  where the coordinate  is the one of the  fiber of the Hopf fibration. 

Let us stress that the main difference with the dyon effect for the ten dimensional KK-monopole is that we need to proyect the M-theory 3-form  on the world-volume coordinates. Moreover, the fact that the so defined 2-form is a pure gauge is reflecting the gauge invariance of the world-volume BI lagrangian. 

Thus in order to compute the electric charge, we parametrize the  as in
V_f_1(r),0,1 2 f_2(r),f_2(r)),
which can be seen to correspond, up to normalization constants, to the vector  plus a deformation coming from the . This allows us to write

C_4 =-1 (2)^3l_s^3/2  2m (r+m)^2 dr.
Dualising this form we find

C_(3) =^* C_4 =-3(4m)^2 2(2)^3l_s^3/2  (r-m r+m )^2ddd,
which is again proportional to the volume of the . This is the electric charge of the KK-monopole, and is well defined at infinity.

Notice that the  part of the dyon moduli space is related to large gauge transformations of the 2-form .

This concludes the proof that the D6-brane interpreted as an eleven dimensional KK-monopole is -as predicted from the ten dimensional open tachyon condensation description-  a dyon. This points out to a deep connection between the gauge-Higgs ten dimensional description of a D6-brane as a  't Hooft-Polyakov monopole and the eleven dimensional  gravitational description. The dyon charge is the most natural bridge between the two descriptions.





